As with hw2, I used the simplest Euclidean distance to measure the correlation distance. This method is the most classical way to compute the distance problem, but can lead to slower runs. The difficulties encountered were mainly over how to make passing chtcs arguments, and while fixing the code made me a bit miserable at times, it really taught me a lot.
library(ggplot2)
library("FITSio")

lists = read.csv('hw4best100.csv')
cB58 = readFrameFromFITS('cB58_Lyman_break.fit')
TOP1:
noisy = readFrameFromFITS(paste("/Users/zhanglanxi/Desktop/605/hw/hw4/data2/6713", lists$spectrumID[1], sep = "/"))
a = scale(noisy[,1])
b = c(rep(0,lists$i[1]-1),scale(cB58[,2]))
df = data.frame(index = c(seq(length(a)),seq(length(b))), flux = c(a,b), 
                  category = c(rep(as.character(lists$spectrumID[1]),length(a)),rep('cB58',length(b))))
ggplot(df,aes(x = index,y = flux)) + geom_line(aes(color = category))
